<tr>
		<td class="contentheading" width="80%">
					New fathers could take 10 months off under shared leave plan 			</td>
				
		
					</tr>
</table>

<table class="contentpaneopen">



<tr>
<td valign="top">
<div id="ctl00_ctl00_MainBodyContent_LeftColumnContent_ArticleBodyPanel"><span id="ctl00_ctl00_MainBodyContent_LeftColumnContent_ph_Body">
<p>New fathers could be able to take up to 10 months’ paid paternity leave under plans outlined by the deputy prime minister Nick Clegg today.<br /><br />A shake-up of parental leave regulations was needed to put an end to the current “Edwardian” rules that “patronise women and marginalise men”, said Clegg.<br /><br />At present, new fathers are entitled to two weeks’ paternity leave, but from April they can ask to take the remaining six months of their partners’ maternity leave if they return to work early. Three months of this will be paid at the statutory rate while the last three months’ leave would be taken unpaid.<br /><br />This legislation was passed by the previous Labour administration, but Clegg said the coalition would consult on a “proper” system of shared parental leave to be introduced in 2015.<br /><br />Speaking at the launch of the <em>Home Front</em> families report from think-tank Demos, Clegg said: “Too many of these parents feel trapped by the current rigid rules. More and more fathers want to play a hands-on role with their young children but too many feel that they can’t. It’s madness that we are denying them that chance.” <br /><br />The Demos report expressed concern about the negative effect that long working hours and demanding jobs could have on parental relationships and children’s upbringing. <br /><br />The government’s proposals would ensure all mothers are still guaranteed the first six weeks off after birth at 90 per cent of their full pay, but Clegg advocated sharing the remaining 46 weeks of parental leave “in a variety of ways”. This <br />means fathers could potentially take all the remaining leave, adding up to ten months in some cases. <br /><br />Clegg said other possible arrangements could include couples being off work concurrently rather than separately, and “blocks of time” being set aside for fathers to promote the uptake of leave.<br /><br />“Both parents could be off at the same time if they wanted to be, and leave could – in agreement with employers – be taken in a number of chunks rather than a single block,” explained Clegg.<br /><br />“Crucially we're also looking at what can be done to encourage men to take more leave. Possibly, for example, through use-it-or-lose it blocks reserved for fathers. International evidence shows how important these can be in increasing take up amongst men.” <br /><br />But business leaders are expected to criticise the recommendations, citing employer concerns about absence management – particularly in small businesses.<br /><br />David Frost, director-general of the British Chambers of Commerce, said: “The plans show a complete lack of understanding of how small businesses work. If men and women have flexible parental leave, how can you plan for the absence and how do you plan for cover?”<br /><br />The CIPD gave the proposals a “cautious welcome”, agreeing in principle but warning that employer uncertainty about the feasibility of new rules should be considered in more detail.<br /><br />“There is no doubt that women are placed at a disadvantage in the labour market by employers’ concerns about the likelihood they will take time off at some stage to start a family,” said Mike Emmott, employee relations adviser at the CIPD. “If men and women have similar entitlements to leave following the birth of a child, this should go a long way to relieving employers of these concerns.”<br /><br />He added: “Employers need to be able to plan ahead with some confidence that they know when individual employees will be available. So the proposal to allow fathers and mothers to take parental leave in blocks for example, rather than all at once, may be a step too far and needs to be looked at carefully.”</p>
<p> </p>
<p>People Management Website 17 Janury 2010</p>
</span></div></td>
</tr>

